Question 6: Create a bar chart of the life expectancy of nations in the âAmericasâ in the year 2007. The countries should be sorted in descending order of life expectancy.

Hint: You will need to use âreorder(country,-lifeExp)â when you define your x variable in the aes. You may find it useful to flip the coordinates (with âcoord_flipâ) to make it easier to read your chart. If you do this, then you should remove theâ-â from in front of âlifeExpâ in your reorder function.

graph2 = gap %>% filter(continent == "Americas")
graph2 = graph2 %>% filter(year == 2007)
graph2  %>% 
ggplot(aes(x=reorder(country,-lifeExp), y=lifeExp)) + geom_bar(stat="identity", alpha=.6, width=.4) +
    coord_flip()+ theme_bw()

Question 7: Use Google to identify the Hex color code for the red in the flag of Peru.

This task will be a bit challenging, but Iâll provide some hints. Our objective is to recreate the chart from Question 6, but with Peruâs bar in the chart colored the red color from the nationâs flag. The remainder of the bars should be gray (use the color âgrey50â). Highlighting Peru is an example of the use of a preattentive attribute.

Hint 1: Weâll use a fill in the aes. The code will look like this:

fill=factor(ifelse(country==âPeruâ,âHighlightedâ,âNormalâ))

This code uses an ifelse statement to determine if the the country in each bar is Peru or not. Peru is added to a group called âHighlightedâ. The other countries are grouped into âNormalâ.

Hint 2: We then use scale_fill_manual to control the colors used in the fill (replace the Xâs in the values below the the Hex code for the red in Peruâs flag):

scale_fill_manual(name = âcountryâ, values=c(â#XXXXXâ,âgrey50â))

graph2 = gap %>% filter(continent == "Americas")
graph2 = graph2 %>% filter(year == 2007)
p <- graph2  %>% 
ggplot()+ aes(x=reorder(country,lifeExp), y = lifeExp, fill=factor(ifelse(country=="Peru","Highlighted","Normal"))) + geom_col() +
    coord_flip()+ theme_bw()
